Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.abstract:
The S3 location of the text file that contains the definition of the custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The general form is

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<bucket-name>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/examplebucket/vocab.txt

For more information about S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies, see Custom Vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeUpdateVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to update. The name is case-sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was completed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: If the TranscriptionJobStatus field is FAILED, a description of the error.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The language code for the input speech.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: outputLocationType
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract:
Indicates the location of the output of the transcription job.

If the value is CUSTOMER_BUCKET then the location is the S3 bucket specified in the outputBucketName field when the transcription job was started with the StartTranscriptionJob operation.

If the value is SERVICE_BUCKET then the output is stored by Amazon Transcribe and can be retrieved using the URI in the GetTranscriptionJob response’s TranscriptFileUri field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.name: transcriptionJobStatus
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJobSum.abstract: The status of the transcription job. When the status is COMPLETED, use the GetTranscriptionJob operation to get the results of the transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: completionTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was completed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: creationTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: A timestamp that shows when the job was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract:
If the TranscriptionJobStatus field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

The FailureReason field can contain one of the following values:

  • Unsupported media format - The media format specified in the MediaFormat field of the request isn’t valid. See the description of the MediaFormat field for a list of valid values.

  • The media format provided does not match the detected media format - The media format of the audio file doesn’t match the format specified in the MediaFormat field in the request. Check the media format of your media file and make sure that the two values match.

  • Invalid sample rate for audio file - The sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz of the request isn’t valid. The sample rate must be between 8000 and 48000 Hertz.

  • The sample rate provided does not match the detected sample rate - The sample rate in the audio file doesn’t match the sample rate specified in the MediaSampleRateHertz field in the request. Check the sample rate of your media file and make sure that the two values match.

  • Invalid file size: file size too large - The size of your audio file is larger than Amazon Transcribe can process. For more information, see Limits in the Amazon Transcribe Developer Guide.

  • Invalid number of channels: number of channels too large - Your audio contains more channels than Amazon Transcribe is configured to process. To request additional channels, see Amazon Transcribe Limits in the Amazon Web Services General Reference.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The language code for the input speech.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that describes the input media for the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: mediaSampleRateHertz
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: The sample rate, in Hertz, of the audio track in the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: Optional settings for the transcription job. Use these settings to turn on speaker recognition, to set the maximum number of speakers that should be identified and to specify a custom vocabulary to use when processing the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.name: transcript
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscriptionJob.ht.abstract: An object that describes the output of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.name: transcriptFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeTranscript.html#/c:.abstract:
The location where the transcription is stored.

Use this URI to access the transcription. If you specified an S3 bucket in the OutputBucketName field when you created the job, this is the URI of that bucket. If you chose to store the transcription in Amazon Transcribe, this is a shareable URL that provides secure access to that location.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: transcriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: An object containing details of the asynchronous transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: The language code for the language used in the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: media
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: An object that describes the input media for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: mediaFormat
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: The format of the input media file.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: mediaSampleRateHertz
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The sample rate, in Hertz, of the audio track in the input media file.

If you do not specify the media sample rate, Amazon Transcribe determines the sample rate. If you specify the sample rate, it must match the sample rate detected by Amazon Transcribe. In most cases, you should leave the MediaSampleRateHertz field blank and let Amazon Transcribe determine the sample rate.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: outputBucketName
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The location where the transcription is stored.

If you set the OutputBucketName, Amazon Transcribe puts the transcription in the specified S3 bucket. When you call the GetTranscriptionJob operation, the operation returns this location in the TranscriptFileUri field. The S3 bucket must have permissions that allow Amazon Transcribe to put files in the bucket. For more information, see Permissions Required for IAM User Roles.

You can specify an AWS Key Management Service (KMS) key to encrypt the output of your transcription using the OutputEncryptionKMSKeyId parameter. If you don’t specify a KMS key, Amazon Transcribe uses the default Amazon S3 key for server-side encryption of transcripts that are placed in your S3 bucket.

If you don’t set the OutputBucketName, Amazon Transcribe generates a pre-signed URL, a shareable URL that provides secure access to your transcription, and returns it in the TranscriptFileUri field. Use this URL to download the transcription.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: outputEncryptionKMSKeyId
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the AWS Key Management Service (KMS) key used to encrypt the output of the transcription job. The user calling the StartTranscriptionJob operation must have permission to use the specified KMS key.

You can use either of the following to identify a KMS key in the current account:

  • KMS Key ID: “1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

  • KMS Key Alias: “alias/ExampleAlias”

You can use either of the following to identify a KMS key in the current account or another account:

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: “arn:aws:kms:region:account ID:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab”

  • ARN of a KMS Key Alias: “arn:aws:kms:region:account ID:alias/ExampleAlias”

If you don’t specify an encryption key, the output of the transcription job is encrypted with the default Amazon S3 key (SSE-S3).

If you specify a KMS key to encrypt your output, you must also specify an output location in the OutputBucketName parameter.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: settings
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: A Settings object that provides optional settings for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.name: transcriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeStartTranscriptionJ.abstract: The name of the job. Note that you can’t use the strings “.” or “..” by themselves as the job name. The name must also be unique within an AWS account.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: channelIdentification
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract:
Instructs Amazon Transcribe to process each audio channel separately and then merge the transcription output of each channel into a single transcription.

Amazon Transcribe also produces a transcription of each item detected on an audio channel, including the start time and end time of the item and alternative transcriptions of the item including the confidence that Amazon Transcribe has in the transcription.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: maxAlternatives
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The number of alternative transcriptions that the service should return. If you specify the MaxAlternatives field, you must set the ShowAlternatives field to true.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: maxSpeakerLabels
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The maximum number of speakers to identify in the input audio. If there are more speakers in the audio than this number, multiple speakers will be identified as a single speaker. If you specify the MaxSpeakerLabels field, you must set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: showAlternatives
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: Determines whether the transcription contains alternative transcriptions. If you set the ShowAlternatives field to true, you must also set the maximum number of alternatives to return in the MaxAlternatives field.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: showSpeakerLabels
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract:
Determines whether the transcription job uses speaker recognition to identify different speakers in the input audio. Speaker recognition labels individual speakers in the audio file. If you set the ShowSpeakerLabels field to true, you must also set the maximum number of speaker labels MaxSpeakerLabels field.

You can’t set both ShowSpeakerLabels and ChannelIdentification in the same request. If you set both, your request returns a BadRequestException.

Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeSettings.html#/c:ob.abstract: The name of a vocabulary to use when processing the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeMedia.html#/c:objc(.name: mediaFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeMedia.html#/c:objc(.abstract:
The S3 location of the input media file. The URI must be in the same region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The general form is:

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<bucket-name>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/examplebucket/example.mp4

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/examplebucket/mediadocs/example.mp4

For more information about S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesRes.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesRes.abstract: The ListVocabularies operation returns a page of vocabularies at a time. The maximum size of the page is set by the MaxResults parameter. If there are more jobs in the list than the page size, Amazon Transcribe returns the NextPage token. Include the token in the next request to the ListVocabularies operation to return in the next page of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesRes.name: vocabularies
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesRes.abstract: A list of objects that describe the vocabularies that match the search criteria in the request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.name: maxResults
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.abstract: The maximum number of vocabularies to return in the response. If there are fewer results in the list, this response contains only the actual results.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.name: nameContains
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.abstract: When specified, the vocabularies returned in the list are limited to vocabularies whose name contains the specified string. The search is case-insensitive, ListVocabularies will return both “vocabularyname” and “VocabularyName” in the response list.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.abstract: If the result of the previous request to ListVocabularies was truncated, include the NextToken to fetch the next set of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.name: stateEquals
Classes/AWSTranscribeListVocabulariesReq.abstract: When specified, only returns vocabularies with the VocabularyState field equal to the specified state.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: The ListTranscriptionJobs operation returns a page of jobs at a time. The maximum size of the page is set by the MaxResults parameter. If there are more jobs in the list than the page size, Amazon Transcribe returns the NextPage token. Include the token in the next request to the ListTranscriptionJobs operation to return in the next page of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: status
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: The requested status of the jobs returned.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: transcriptionJobSummaries
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: A list of objects containing summary information for a transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: jobNameContains
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: When specified, the jobs returned in the list are limited to jobs whose name contains the specified string.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: maxResults
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: The maximum number of jobs to return in the response. If there are fewer results in the list, this response contains only the actual results.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: nextToken
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: If the result of the previous request to ListTranscriptionJobs was truncated, include the NextToken to fetch the next set of jobs.

Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.name: status
Classes/AWSTranscribeListTranscriptionJo.abstract: When specified, returns only transcription jobs with the specified status. Jobs are ordered by creation date, with the newest jobs returned first. If you don’t specify a status, Amazon Transcribe returns all transcription jobs ordered by creation date.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: downloadUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The S3 location where the vocabulary is stored. Use this URI to get the contents of the vocabulary. The URI is available for a limited time.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: If the VocabularyState field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was last modified.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyRespon.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to return.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyReques.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetVocabularyReques.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to return information about. The name is case-sensitive.

Classes/AWSTranscribeGetTranscriptionJob.name: transcriptionJob
Classes/AWSTranscribeGetTranscriptionJob.abstract: An object that contains the results of the transcription job.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary to delete.

Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteTranscription.name: transcriptionJobName
Classes/AWSTranscribeDeleteTranscription.abstract: The name of the transcription job to be deleted.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: failureReason
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: If the VocabularyState field is FAILED, this field contains information about why the job failed.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: lastModifiedTime
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The date and time that the vocabulary was created.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.name: vocabularyState
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyRes.abstract: The processing state of the vocabulary. When the VocabularyState field contains READY the vocabulary is ready to be used in a StartTranscriptionJob request.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: The language code of the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: phrases
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: An array of strings that contains the vocabulary entries.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyFileUri
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract:
The S3 location of the text file that contains the definition of the custom vocabulary. The URI must be in the same region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The general form is

https://s3.<aws-region>.amazonaws.com/<bucket-name>/<keyprefix>/<objectkey>

For example:

https://s3.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/examplebucket/vocab.txt

For more information about S3 object names, see Object Keys in the Amazon S3 Developer Guide.

For more information about custom vocabularies, see Custom Vocabularies.

Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.name: vocabularyName
Classes/AWSTranscribeCreateVocabularyReq.abstract: The name of the vocabulary. The name must be unique within an AWS account. The name is case-sensitive.
